#  SubstitutionModels.Q     Function .  Generate a Q matrix for a  NucleicAcidSubstitutionModel , of the form:  math   Q =  egin{bmatrix}   Q_{A, A}   Q_{A, C}   Q_{A, G}   Q_{A, T} 
  Q_{C, A}   Q_{C, C}   Q_{C, G}   Q_{C, T} 
  Q_{G, A}   Q_{G, C}   Q_{G, G}   Q_{G, T} 
  Q_{T, A}   Q_{T, C}   Q_{T, G}   Q_{T, T} nd{bmatrix}.  source  #  SubstitutionModels.P     Function .  Generate a P matrix for a  NucleicAcidSubstitutionModel , of the form:  math   P =  egin{bmatrix}   P_{A, A}   P_{A, C}   P_{A, G}   P_{A, T} 
  P_{C, A}   P_{C, C}   P_{C, G}   P_{C, T} 
  P_{G, A}   P_{G, C}   P_{G, G}   P_{G, T} 
  P_{T, A}   P_{T, C}   P_{T, G}   P_{T, T} nd{bmatrix}.  for specified time  source

The set of substitution models included in this package is easily extended with user defined types. When defining a new substitution model, the minimum requirement is that it is a subtype of  NucleicAcidSubstitutionModel , and that it has a valid method for the  Q  function. If a method for the  P  function for  a substitution model is not defined, P matrices will be calculated using the  matrix exponential as follows:  $$
P = \text{expm} \left(Q \times t \right).
$$  For many substitution models the P matrix has a known form. Rather than approximate and actually using julia's  expm  each time a P matrix required can be avoided by defining a method  for the  P  function, typically resulting in substantial computational savings.  A user defined substitution model may be described as a special case of the Generalized Time Reversible model (GTR), which has a Q matrix of the form:  $$
Q = \begin{bmatrix}
-(\delta \pi_{\text{C}} + \eta \pi_{\text{G}} + \beta \pi_{\text{T}})  
\delta \pi_{\text{C}}  
\eta \pi_{\text{G}}  
\beta \pi_{\text{T}} \
\delta \pi_{\text{A}}  
-(\delta \pi_{\text{A}} + \epsilon \pi_{\text{G}} + \alpha \pi_{\text{T}})  
\epsilon \pi_{\text{G}}  
\alpha \pi_{\text{T}} \
\eta \pi_{\text{A}}  
\epsilon \pi_{\text{C}}  
-(\eta \pi_{\text{A}} + \epsilon \pi_{\text{C}} + \gamma \pi_{\text{T}})  
\gamma \pi_{\text{T}}) \
-(\beta \pi_{\text{A}} + \alpha \pi_{\text{C}} + \gamma \pi{\text{G}})  
\beta \pi_{\text{A}}  
\alpha \pi_{\text{C}}  
\gamma \pi{\text{G}})
\end{bmatrix}.
$$  A new  NucleicAcidSubstitutionModel  may be described by defining a new method for each of the following internal functions:  _α ,  _β ,  _γ ,  _δ ,  _ϵ , and  _η . Additionally, if there are unequal base frequencies for this substitution model, methods for  _πA ,  _πC ,  _πG , and  _πT  will need to be defined.   SubstitutionModels.NucleicAcidSubstitutionModel  SubstitutionModels.P  SubstitutionModels.Q
